            ]
        },
        {
            "cell_type": "markdown",
            "metadata": {},
            "source": [
                "## 1. The Recurrent Paradigm: LSTMs and the Memory Bottleneck\n",
                "The LSTM (Long Short-Term Memory) network was designed to mitigate the vanishing gradient problem in standard RNNs by introducing a cell state ($c_t$) and gating mechanisms.\n",
                "\n",
                "### Mathematical Formulation:\n",
                "For an input $x_t$, the LSTM updates its hidden state $h_t$ and cell state $c_t$ as follows:\n",
                "$$ f_t = \\sigma(W_f x_t + U_f h_{t-1} + b_f) \\quad \\text{(Forget Gate)} $$\n",
                "$$ i_t = \\sigma(W_i x_t + U_i h_{t-1} + b_i) \\quad \\text{(Input Gate)} $$\n",
                "$$ o_t = \\sigma(W_o x_t + U_o h_{t-1} + b_o) \\quad \\text{(Output Gate)} $$\n",
                "$$ \\tilde{c}_t = \\tanh(W_c x_t + U_c h_{t-1} + b_c) $$\n",
                "$$ c_t = f_t \\odot c_{t-1} + i_t \\odot \\tilde{c}_t $$\n",
                "$$ h_t = o_t \\odot \\tanh(c_t) $$\n",
                "\n",
                "### Limitations in Momentum Trading:\n",
                "1. **Information Decay:** Despite gating, LSTMs struggle to maintain precise information over very long horizons (e.g., 252 days). The cell state acts as a compressed bottleneck.\n",
                "2. **Sequential Dependency:** The computation at $t$ depends on $t-1$, preventing parallelization and making the model sensitive to local noise.\n",
                "3. **Interpretability:** The 'gates' provide some insight, but they don't explicitly show *which* specific past event is driving today's decision."
            ]
        },
        {
            "cell_type": "markdown",
            "metadata": {},
            "source": [
                "## 2. The Attention Paradigm: Transformers and Direct Dependencies\n",
                "The Momentum Transformer replaces the recurrent state with a self-attention mechanism, which directly connects every time step in the lookback window.\n",
                "\n",
                "### Multi-Head Attention:\n",
                "$$ \\text{Attention}(Q, K, V) = \\text{softmax}\\left(\\frac{QK^T}{\\sqrt{d_k}}\\right)V $$\n",
                "\n",
                "### Strategic Advantages:\n",
                "1. **Constant Path Length:** The path between any two time steps is $O(1)$, effectively eliminating the vanishing gradient problem across long horizons.\n",
                "2. **Regime Identification:** Attention maps provide a direct visualization of the model's 'memory.' We can see if the model is currently attending to the 2008 crisis or the 2020 crash to inform its current position.\n",
                "3. **Variable Selection Network (VSN):** Wood et al. integrate a VSN to automate the ranking of features (e.g., MACD-10 vs MACD-252) at each time step."
            ]
        },
        {
            "cell_type": "markdown",
            "metadata": {},
            "source": [
                "## 3. The 'Gating Gap' and Structural Integrity\n",
                "A key contribution of the Momentum Transformer is the use of **Gated Residual Networks (GRN)**. These allow the model to skip non-linear processing when the signal-to-noise ratio is low, reverting to a simpler linear model to prevent overfitting.\n",
                "\n",
                "### GRN Mechanism:\n",
                "$$ GRN(\\eta) = \\text{LayerNorm}(\\eta + GLU(\\text{Linear}(\\text{Linear}(\\eta)))) $$\n",
                "\n",
                "This structural flexibility is what allows the Momentum Transformer to survive the 'Non-Stationarity Trap' that often causes unconstrained LSTMs to collapse out-of-sample."
            ]
